		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Mining-the-wealth-of-the-world-s-seed-banks" title="Mining the wealth of the world's seed banks" alt="link">Mining the wealth of the world's seed banks</a></h2>

	
					<p>In a recent Comment in <i>Nature</i>, Cornell University plant geneticist Susan McCouch and colleagues says that the biodiversity stored in plant gene banks coupled with advances in genetics &nbsp;and plant breeding may hold the keys for meeting the challenge of climate change, soil degradation and water and land shortages. Though seeds are readily accessible in 1,700 gene banks, &nbsp;it is difficult for breeders to make use of the wealth of genetic material in seed banks because of a lack of information about the genes in most plants and the traits they confer. The paper &nbsp;outlines a plan to address these constraints: 1) a massive genetic sequencing effort on seed-bank holdings; 2) a broad phenotyping initiative; 3) an internationally accessible informatics &nbsp;infrastructure.<a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-07/cu-tft070513.php" target="_self">http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-07/cu-tft070513.php</a>&nbsp;(Eurekalert, 05/07/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Mining-the-wealth-of-the-world-s-seed-banks">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action" title="The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action" alt="link">The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action</a></h2>

	
					<p>Indices and maps of global hidden hunger are being developed to help prioritise programme assistance and to serve as an evidence-based global advocacy tool. In this research paper, &nbsp;Sumithra Muthayya of Sax Institute Sydney, Australia together with specialists from both the non-profit and for-profit nutrition sectors, creates two types of hidden hunger indices and maps &nbsp;(using data on stunting, anaemia, retinol levels and estimates of Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALYs) attributed to micronutrient deficiencies). Of note, occurrence of iodine deficiency did &nbsp;not conform to that of other micronutrients (it mainly occurs in developed countries). The study demonstrates how these indices and maps provide crucial data for tackling global multiple &nbsp;micronutrient deficiencies and could help to scale up effective nutrition interventions.(<i>PLoS ONE</i> 8(6): e67860. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0067860. June 2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Tomato-fruits-a-good-target-for-iodine-biofortification" title="Tomato fruits: a good target for iodine biofortification" alt="link">Tomato fruits: a good target for iodine biofortification</a></h2>

	
					<p>Iodine deficiency affects two billion people worldwide. This experiment conducted by the PlantLab, Italy and the private company SQM S.A., Chile evaluated the possibility of biofortifying &nbsp;tomato fruits with iodine. Results showed that the use of iodized salts induced a significant increase in the fruit’s iodine content in doses that did not affect plant growth and development. &nbsp;This suggests that the tomato is a particularly suitable crop for iodine biofortification programmes. The pattern and magnitude of iodine deficiency does not conform to that of other &nbsp;micronutrients. The greatest proportions of children with iodine deficiency are in the Eastern Mediterranean (46.6%), European (44.2%), and African (40.4%) regions. The daily Dietary &nbsp;Reference Intake (USA) for iodine is between 110 µg for infants and 290 µg for lactating mothers. Some foods are naturally rich in iodine: beans, potatoes (with skin), gray (rock) salt, sea &nbsp;vegetables (kelp), yoghurt.(<i>Front. Plant Sci.</i> 4:205. doi: 10.3389/fpls.2013.00205 ; 27/06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Tomato-fruits-a-good-target-for-iodine-biofortification">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Proteins-called-membrane-transporters-will-be-key-to-sustainable-food-production" title="Proteins called membrane transporters will be key to sustainable food production" alt="link">Proteins called membrane transporters will be key to sustainable food production</a></h2>

	
					<p>Recent developments in understanding the biology of plant transporters are leading to improved varieties less susceptible to adverse environments and for improving human health. Membrane transporters are a class of specialised proteins that plants use to take up nutrients from the soil, resist toxic metals and pests, increase salt and drought tolerance, control water loss and store sugar. By improving current staple crops by modifying how transporters work in the plants, the biologists behind the discoveries believe crops could be made more efficient in using water, acquiring soil nutrients, etc., and taht growing them would directly reduce the environmental impacts of agriculture. By disseminating these findings widely, the researchers hope to educate policy makers and speed the eventual application of their discoveries to global agriculture. Challenges remain, but this is a promising research avenue. Are such improved food plants considered GMOs? Are they part of the next generation of transgenic crops that may well benefit food insecure regions of the world? &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-05/uoc--npp042913.php?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank">Eurek</a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-05/nbi-mfa042613.php?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank">Alert</a>, 01/05/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Proteins-called-membrane-transporters-will-be-key-to-sustainable-food-production">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Best-practices-for-organic-agriculture-policy-in-developing-countries" title="Best practices for organic agriculture policy in developing countries" alt="link">Best practices for organic agriculture policy in developing countries</a></h2>

	
					<p>This UNCTA-UNEP/CBTF study recommends that developing country governments should play a facilitating role and engage with stakeholders when developing their organic policies. It presents an evaluation of several country case studies (South Africa). It notes that compliance with international standards is necessary if countries are to realise the benefits from organic agriculture and that they should build the requisite capacities through education, research, extension and other aspects. Recommendations are made for general policy, standards and regulations, markets, production and other including, training, education and research. The need for specialised research and development programmes and prioritisation of organic research avenues is acknowledged. &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.unep.ch/etb/publications/UNCTAD_DITC_TED_2007_3.pdf?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_self">UNEP-UNCTAD</a>, 2008)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Best-practices-for-organic-agriculture-policy-in-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
