</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Edible-insects-in-a-food-safety-and-nutritional-perspective-a-critical-review" title="Edible insects in a food safety and nutritional perspective: a critical review " alt="link">Edible insects in a food safety and nutritional perspective: a critical review </a></h2>

	
					<p>This paper evaluates how insects could be safely used as food and discusses nutritional data to justify why insect food sources can no longer be neglected by legislators. As new ways must be found to increase yields while preserving food quality, natural habitats, and biodiversity, the authors show how insects could be of great interest as a possible solution due to their capability to satisfy 2 different requirements: (i) they are an important source of protein and other nutrients; (ii) their use as food has ecological advantages over conventional meat and, in the long run, economic benefits. (<a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1541-4337.12014/abstract?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_April2013" target="_blank"><i>Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety</i></a>, Vol. 12, No. 3, 2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Edible-insects-in-a-food-safety-and-nutritional-perspective-a-critical-review">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Farming-Change-Growing-more-food-with-a-changing-resource-base" title="Farming Change: Growing more food with a changing resource base" alt="link">Farming Change: Growing more food with a changing resource base</a></h2>

	
					<p>This publication combines three inter-related papers on Caribbean agriculture on growing food crops without soil, securing ecosystems services of forest cover and combating invasive alien species.<a href="http://www.cta.int/en/About-us/New-Publications/Farming-Change-Growing-more-food-with-a-changing-resource-base" target="_self">http://www.cta.int/en/About-us/New-Publications/Farming-Change-Growing-more-food-with-a-changing-resource-base</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Farming-Change-Growing-more-food-with-a-changing-resource-base">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/A-review-of-global-scenario-exercises-for-food-security-analysis-Assumptions-and-results" title="A review of global scenario exercises for food security analysis: Assumptions and results" alt="link">A review of global scenario exercises for food security analysis: Assumptions and results</a></h2>

	
					<p>This review focuses on nine global food security scenarios, all of which only deal with two of the four dimensions of food security: availability and accessibility. Food utilisation and stability are hardly covered.<a href="http://www.foodsecure.eu/PublicationDetail.aspx?id=9" target="_self">http://www.foodsecure.eu/PublicationDetail.aspx?id=9</a><a href="http://www.wageningenur.nl/en/show/New-agricultural-realities-require-improvements-in-the-assessment-of-food-security.htm" target="_self">http://www.wageningenur.nl/en/show/New-agricultural-realities-require-improvements-in-the-assessment-of-food-security.htm</a>(LEI Wageningen UR, 14/02/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/A-review-of-global-scenario-exercises-for-food-security-analysis-Assumptions-and-results">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/New-cowpea-varieties-offer-promise" title="New cowpea varieties offer promise" alt="link">New cowpea varieties offer promise</a></h2>

	
					<p>The new cowpea varieties combine extra-early maturity, high protein and high yield potential with resistance to major diseases and tolerance to heat and drought.<a href="http://today.agrilife.org/2013/04/10/new-cowpea-varieties-offer-promise-in-south-africa-other-parts-of-the-world/" target="_self">http://today.agrilife.org/2013/04/10/new-cowpea-varieties-offer-promise-in-south-africa-other-parts-of-the-world/</a>(AgriLife Today, 10/04/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/New-cowpea-varieties-offer-promise">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Fighting-hunger-with-micronutrient-rich-crops-and-diverse-food" title="Fighting hunger with micronutrient-rich crops and diverse food" alt="link">Fighting hunger with micronutrient-rich crops and diverse food</a></h2>

	
					<p>An interview featuring Howarth Bouis, director of HarvestPlus, a programme that promotes micronutrient-rich staple food crops through biofortification that offers a good overview of the latest research on the subject.<a href="http://www.cgiar.org/consortium-news/tackling-malnutrition-means-quality-as-well-as-quantity/" target="_self">http://www.cgiar.org/consortium-news/tackling-malnutrition-means-quality-as-well-as-quantity/</a>(CGIAR, 9/04/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Fighting-hunger-with-micronutrient-rich-crops-and-diverse-food">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Participation-of-smallholders-in-agricultural-markets-in-Papua-New-Guinea" title="Participation of smallholders in agricultural markets in Papua New Guinea" alt="link">Participation of smallholders in agricultural markets in Papua New Guinea</a></h2>

	
					<p>Upali Wickramasinghe, Regional Adviser on Poverty Reduction and Food Security at UNCAPSA-ESCAP, writes the mismatch between current performance and potential of Papua New Guinea agricultural sector. Among the imperatives needed to 70% of PNG’s subsistence farmers in SMEs by 2030, the author suggests the development of efficient land administration, roads and supply chains to link producers and markets, enforcing CODEX marketing standards, and the implementation of a set of policies that would allow smallholders to seek greater specialization and reduce market participation costs. This may well require the development of a comprehensive agricultural information system covering the entire country.<a href="http://www.uncapsa.org/LIBRARYJournal_detail.asp?VJournalKey=886" target="_self">http://www.uncapsa.org/LIBRARYJournal_detail.asp?VJournalKey=886</a>(UNCAPSA, 12/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Participation-of-smallholders-in-agricultural-markets-in-Papua-New-Guinea">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Name-brand-products-boon-or-bust-for-farmers-and-consumers" title="Name-brand products: boon or bust for farmers and consumers?" alt="link">Name-brand products: boon or bust for farmers and consumers?</a></h2>

	
					<p>Published by IFPRI, this study conducted in 2012 looks into locals brands and how they reshape agricultural value chains and consumers habits. Examining the makhana (<i>Euryale ferox</i>) value chain in Bihar, India, the authors noted the emergence of more expensive packed and branded products but that their effect on consumers is ambiguous. While the emergence of brands leads to increasing differentiation in retail markets, the brands in these settings provide mostly incomplete or misleading information for the consumer, and the quality of products contained in branded bags is often lower than for loose products. The authors also found that farmers realize few direct benefits from the presence of these brands.<a href="http://www.ifpri.org/blog/name-brand-products-boon-or-bust-farmers-and-consumers" target="_self">http://www.ifpri.org/blog/name-brand-products-boon-or-bust-farmers-and-consumers</a>(IFPRI, 2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Name-brand-products-boon-or-bust-for-farmers-and-consumers">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Greater-Sago-use-will-help-to-promote-food-security-in-the-Pacific" title="Greater Sago use will help to promote food security in the Pacific " alt="link">Greater Sago use will help to promote food security in the Pacific </a></h2>

	
					<p>The launch of the Regional Sago Network for Asia and the Pacific (SNAP) in March 2013 marks the promotion of underutilized indigenous food crops such as Sago palm. Sago has a high starch yield potential and grows in swamps and wetlands with minimal competition from other food crops for land and water use. Sago has many advantages over other starch-producing food crops. It can grow in swamps and wet land which are not suitable for agricultural production. It is tolerant to drought and floods. It increases farm household income and employment through the production of confectionery and cookies, roofing material from leaves and the production of woven mats and handicrafts. The Sago worm cultured from old Sego trunks is a local delicacy with high market value. Additionally it contributes to slowing the pace of global warming through its year-round carbon dioxide absorbing function.&nbsp;(<a href="http://www.fao.org/asiapacific/rap/home/news/detail/en/?news_uid=172925" target="_blank">FAO</a>, 14/12/2012)&nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Food-security/Related-developments/Greater-Sago-use-will-help-to-promote-food-security-in-the-Pacific">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
